Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: The original idea of channel-wise kernel heterogeneity via differentiable routing is strong, but it assumes a static, pre-defined set of kernel types (1D/2D/3D) and applies them uniformly across spatial-temporal dimensions. Drawing inspiration from Papers 2 and 3—particularly the use of adaptive structural modeling (e.g., recurrent encoding over local regions and anisotropic filtering based on neighborhood structure)—I propose a shift from *fixed* kernel type selection to *dynamically synthesized* convolutional operators that are not only dimensionally adaptive but also *geometrically conditioned* on local input patterns. Instead of selecting among discrete 1D/2D/3D kernels, the network should learn to generate hybrid, sub-kernel compositions tailored per channel and local receptive field. This introduces a new level of adaptivity: rather than choosing "what kind of convolution," the model learns "how to construct the optimal convolution" by assembling sparse, directional primitives (e.g., axial 1D filters along time, height, width, or diagonal paths) into heterogeneous channel-specific operators. This approach moves beyond architecture search toward *on-the-fly operator synthesis*, enabling fine-grained spatiotemporal specialization while promoting functional diversity through geometry-aware inductive bias. Unlike CAKES, which shrinks kernels via discrete rules, or static mixture models, this method enables continuous, gradient-based learning of both kernel shape and connectivity, leading to higher efficiency and better interpretability. By integrating dynamic filter generation with locality-sensitive routing, we achieve a more principled decomposition of 3D operations that aligns with semantic content (e.g., motion along time vs. texture in space), improving both accuracy and resource utilization.

